Exercise 7.2

df <- read.csv("mygardens.txt", header=TRUE, sep='\t')
ozone = df$ozone
garden = df$garden
N = length(ozone)

Part (a)

plot(1:N, ozone, xlab="N", ylab="ozone", xlim=c(0, N), ylim=c(0, max(ozone)+1))
mean_overall = mean(ozone)
lines(1:N, matrix(mean_overall, N, 1))
for(i in 1:N) {
  segments(i, mean_overall, i, ozone[i])
}

df_a = df[df$garden == 'A',]
df_b = df[df$garden == 'B',]
ozone_a = df_a$ozone
ozone_b = df_b$ozone
mean_a = mean(ozone_a)
mean_b = mean(ozone_b)

plot(1, type="n", xlab="N", ylab="ozone", xlim=c(0, N), ylim=c(0, max(ozone)+1))
lines(1:N, matrix(mean_a, N, 1), col='red')
lines(1:N, matrix(mean_b, N, 1), col='blue')
for(i in 1:N){
  if (df$garden[i] == 'A') {
    points(i, df$ozone[i], col='red')
    segments(i, mean_a, i, df$ozone[i], col='red')
  } else {
    points(i, df$ozone[i], col='blue')
    segments(i, mean_b, i, df$ozone[i], col='blue')
  }
}
legend(0, 2, inset = .05, legend=c("Garden A", "Garden B"), col=c("red","blue"), pch=c(16,16), bg=c("white","white"), title="Legend")

Part (b)

D_b_hat = length(ozone_a)*(mean_a - mean_overall)^2 + length(ozone_b)*(mean_b - mean_overall)^2
print(c('D_b_hat = ', D_b_hat))
## [1] "D_b_hat = " "20"
D_i_hat = sum((ozone_a - mean_a)^2) + sum((ozone_b - mean_b)^2)
print(c('D_i_hat = ', D_i_hat))
## [1] "D_i_hat = " "24"
D_g_hat = D_b_hat + D_i_hat
print(c('D_g_hat = ', D_g_hat))
## [1] "D_g_hat = " "44"
p = 2
R = ((N-p)/(p-1))*(D_b_hat/D_i_hat)
print(R)
## [1] 15
if (R>qf(0.95,p-1,N-p)) {
  print('There is a significant difference between gardens A and B wrt ozone concentration at significance level 0.05')
}
## [1] "There is a significant difference between gardens A and B wrt ozone concentration at significance level 0.05"

From looking at the matrix and saying something is highly correlated if the absolute value of the correlation is larger 0.9 one observes the pairs (Density, BodyFat), (Abdomen, Chest) and (Hip, Weight) are extremely correlated. One might also observe that Weight has a high correlation (>0.8) to almost half of the variables and it is noticeable that Abdomen has the highest correlation to BodyFat excluding density which is very interesting since we try to predict the body fat.

From the Adjusted R-squared statistic i decided to proceed without the intercept. From now on I test the model always with every possible new variable and compare the Multiple/Adjusted R-squared from the more complex model with the old model. Selection of a new parameter or stopping will be done by hand and not by a predefined algorithm. One more criteria for stopping is the significance of the individual parameters.

adjusted_R <- function(new_variable) {
  model2 <- lm(data$BodyFat ~ data$Abdomen - 1 + data[,new_variable])
  print(new_variable)
  print(summary(model2)$r.squared)
  print(summary(model2)$adj.r.squared)
}

  model2 <- lm(data$BodyFat ~ data$Abdomen + data$Wrist + data$Hip + data$Neck + data$Forearm + data$Age + data$Thigh - 1 + data[,new_variable])
  print(new_variable)
  print(summary(model2)$r.squared)
  print(summary(model2)$adj.r.squared)
}

Overall the fit of my model is fine as the R values suggest. Taking out the Intercept really improved the models performance as I also tried more complex models with the intercept and it always performed much worse than any model without an intercept. In the context Abdomen really estimates the BodyFat best because most fat lies there. Thigh is basically the same only that it is not as significant as the Abdomen. Age is good since people tend to get a little bit less fit as they get older which contributes to a higher bodyfat percentage. Hip is negative as it kind of complements the abdomen. Abdomen size is not only conditional on bodyfat but also other factors which also contributes to the Hip. So i guess Hip subtracts the part of abdomen out which is not due to bodyfat but other factors. Neck is kinda unclear how it contributes but I think a larger neck is a size for overall much muscle which contributes also to less bodyfat.

The data points I removed had so much more leverage than all the other data points that I think I get a more balanced data set by removing them.
